{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491543"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:52:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:52:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"977"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/977"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.13,0.78,0.05,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"977"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114822"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/977"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"977"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96826"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"489"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13161"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31700"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42187"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43054"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44263"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114822"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 29-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with chest pain and shortness of breath. The pain came on a few hours ago and is worse when she breathes in deeply. She is 29 weeks pregnant, but otherwise has no medical conditions. On examination the patient has a BMI of 23, is afebrile, tachycardic and tachypnoeic, and her chest is clear. She has a reddened right calf that is tender and warm to touch.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFetal ultrasound for amniotic fluid index and Dopplers and CTG are normal. An ECG performed shows sinus tachycardia, and renal function tests come back normal. A lower limb Doppler ultrasound is performed and confirms a DVT in the right lower limb. Some form of anticoagulation is required.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Warfarin","Apixaban","Enoxaparin","Aspirin and Clopidogrel (DAPT)","Danaparoid"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPregnancy is associated with a 4-5-fold increase in the risk of VTE compared to age-matched non-pregnant women due to the increase in venous stasis, procoagulants and the pro-inflammatory effect of pregnancy on vessel walls. There is an overlap of dyspnoea, tachycardia and leg swelling which can be normal physiological changes of pregnancy or pathological signs of PE.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u00a0The above picture is typical of a pulmonary embolism, supporting this differential are acute onset shortness of breath and pleuritic chest pain, pre-syncope, and sinus tachycardia on ECG. The typical lower limb signs mean that a directed lower limb doppler can be performed as a first line investigation, because if this is positive, therapeutic enoxaparin will be indicated and a V/Q scan or CT pulmonary angiogram can be avoided.\u00a0\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter diagnosis, \u003Cstrong\u003Eenoxaparin\u003C/strong\u003E, a low molecular weight heparin (LMWH) at a dose of 1mg/Kg BD or 1.5mg/kg daily, is the anticoagulant of choice\u00a0antenatally. \u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E is category D in pregnancy and should be avoided as it is associated with increased rates of miscarriage, fetal teratogenicity and fetal and maternal haemorrhagic complications. Postnatally, enoxaparin and warfarin are safe in breastfeeding and either can\u00a0be used.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is currently insufficient data to support the safe use of the NOACs such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eapixaban\u003C/strong\u003E in pregnancy or breastfeeding. There is no role for antiplatelet agents in the treatment of deep vein thrombosis, therefore dual antiplatelet therapy with \u003Cstrong\u003Easpirin and clopidogrel\u003C/strong\u003E is not correct.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDanaparoid\u003C/strong\u003E works as an anticoagulant by inactivating clotting factors\u00a0IIa (thrombin) and Xa by binding to antithrombin\u00a0III. It is indicated upon specialist advice for the treatment of thromboembolic disease in patients with (or with a history of) heparin-induced thrombocytopenia with heparin or LMWH. It is considered safe in pregnancy however would not be the first line agent of choice.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pregnancy is associated with a 4-5-fold increase in the risk of VTE compared to age-matched non-pregnant women due to the increase in venous stasis, procoagulants and the pro-inflammatory effect of pregnancy on vessel walls."],"references":["van der Pol LM, Tromeur C, Bistervels IM, et al. Pregnancy-Adapted YEARS Algorithm for Diagnosis of Suspected Pulmonary Embolism. N Engl J Med. 2019;380(12):1139\u20101149. doi:10.1056/NEJMoa1813865","South Australian Perinatal Practice Guideline 2020, Thromboprophylaxis and Thromboembolic Disease in Pregnancy, Department of Health and Aging, Adelaide, viewed 7/8/2020, \u003Chttps://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/a070e7804eedf080b699b76a7ac0d6e4/Thromboprophylaxis+and+Thromboembolic+Disease+in+Pregnancy_PPG_v4_1_14052018.pdf?MOD=AJPERES\u0026amp;CACHEID=ROOTWORKSPACE-a070e7804eedf080b699b76a7ac0d6e4-n5ifkRg\u003E."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96826"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"977"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96826"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-20T17:13:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-20T17:13:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"977"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114822"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":